properties.cultural_interests: Very diverse community - socio economic, religious, race etc.  That is a strength of our community. properties.economic_interests: Shared economic interests are shared with southeast michigan.  People that live in our community work west as far as Ann Arbor and east as far as Detroit, plus both north and south.  Shared economic interest is more in line with property tax revenues as opposed to jobs.
properties.comm_activities: Combined Farmington Hills and Farmington share school system.  There is a downtown area in Farmington that is shared - by some and is gaining momentum through farmers market, community concerts, skate park etc..  There is also a community center at the Costick Center in north Farmington.  And a sports complex at Founders Park enjoyed primarily by youth sports.  However, the community - other than through schools - does not seem to have a single central gathering place.
properties.other_considerations: Continuing to foster a diverse community.  Farmington / Farmington Hills is what i would view as our community.

properties.entry_name: School Districts of Chelsea, Dexter, Manchester, and Saline
properties.cultural_interests: Each town's local schools provide a major sense of belonging. We are mostly an area of low diversity both in ethnicity and religion (Caucasian, Christian). We value education and support our local fitness facilities. We also work to support our local economies.
properties.economic_interests: My community surrounds the west and south sides of Ann Arbor. There are a few dominant sources of employment available. These include farming, the local schools, medical facilities, local manufacturing, main street stores and restaurants, and we serve as a bedroom community for Ann Arbor and the University of Michigan.
properties.comm_activities: Our small towns each have vibrant central "downtown" areas, we have access to many town, county, and state parks and recreation areas, including a portion of the "Border to Border" trail and the Huron and Raisin Rivers. 3 out of the 4 towns have supermarkets. Chelsea has a hospital which is affiliated with the 2 large hospitals in Ann Arbor. Chelsea and Dexter each have successful community theaters. We do go to Ann Arbor frequently to obtain services and recreation not available at home.
properties.other_considerations: Our schools, with the help of the Washtenaw Intermediate School District, share resources and work together on programming and other educational issues. Sharing the same representatives in Lansing and Washington DC would be helpful to have our voices be heard.

properties.cultural_interests: A rural community with strong family values.  Many of the people represent as being culturally conservative
properties.economic_interests: I live in a very rural community, with no grocery stores, limited broadband, large corporate farms, and a small school district that is further away then the nearest school actually is (because of district lines).
properties.comm_activities: Most services are in nearby Battle Creek, there are few places where people in the community socialize outside of the post office and a few churches.

properties.entry_name: Village of Goodrich & surrounding community (Atlas Township)
properties.economic_interests: My community is a rural suburb. There are some small working farms, but many people who live here commute to nearby cities to work.

properties.cultural_interests: Many of us moved here because of the beauty of the natural surroundings. We want to preserve this beauty.
properties.economic_interests: Loch Alpine is an unincorporated development of over 400 homes. Our shared concerns are environmental. Our homes were built around a golf course that is no longer viable; the fate of this land is now uncertain. A developer want to build new homes that will decrease the value of current residents' homes and deprive us of beautiful open space. Loch Alpine has a stream and two small lakes impacted by farming practices upstream. We share a community well, too, and water quality is always a concern.

properties.cultural_interests: Mostly friendly people and families.  We need more events in the summer, we once had Arts, Beats and Eats.  Our library children department is good, but needs upgrading for the teens and adults.  Many churches reached out before Covid 19.  Pontiac has poor , working class , and middle class people trying to survive day to day.  We just want a good city without crime and drugs, and trouble.   (Limit the problems ) We have all races here.
properties.economic_interests: No, shared economy here.  We, in Pontiac, MI..need large corporations to come in.  We once had a good economy with General Motors, but they scaled down to Engineering only and that skill does not match the majority who live here.   Pontiac, MI is a city by itself. Our water is now with the county since Emergency Management.  They are trying to fix the quality of taste and a bad sewer smell near MLK Blvd.   Sometimes contractors , landlords or plain people dump trash and furniture.
properties.comm_activities:
The seniors have two community centers..both now closed to Covid 19.  We have a very nice park Beaudette park AKA Mill Dam.  The other parks are smaller or have to come up to par in repair.  We have several community service agencies here.  Our County helps us now, more than in the past.
We need more tutoring centers and activities for the children and teens.  Needs major Grocery stores, we used to have them but they moved when General Motors departed.  Schools need help in academic area.
properties.other_considerations: Put Martin Luther King between Perry and Featherstone back  into District 6.   It was too confusing for the people who live there when they placed it in District 7   Put Court St in Precinct 16,  it used to be Precinct 24.  Stop the confusion.   I do not want Marijuana grower, and processor near my home.  I think the Glenwood plaza should be a Grocery store and restaurants, minor repair places.   Keep my area the way it is it nice.

properties.cultural_interests: There is a true sense of community where the area is one big family that depends on each other. The area is predominately Black,but there are other nationalities that include  the Latino, Whites and the Hmongs.   There are a lot of religious groups and  a few art centers in  the 48342 zip code. The downtown is a business oasis.  United Shores is in the heart of 48342 community and Amazon is building on the old Pontiac Silverdome site.
properties.economic_interests: The people living in  my community are primarily black or African American. The number of people in their late 20s to early 40s s extremely large while the number of young adults is large. There are also an extremely large number of single parents and an extremely small number of families. Our zip code is part of  Oakland County  and the community borders Auburn Hills. There are concerns about the water quality within the city.
properties.comm_activities:
The Art Experience, the Pontiac Creative Arts Center, Pontiac Public Library , Murphy Park,  Mattie Hatchett  Park, the Oakland County Historical Society, Churches such as Macedonia Missionary Baptist Church, M-1 Concourse, Downtown Pontiac, Alleycat Cafe, Smash Kickboxing, Anytime Fitness, Downtown Food Eateries. 

The community get services like groceries mostly outside of the community. The only food resources are corner stores and a few food marts.
properties.other_considerations: Our community cares about having a community recreation center for all ages,  activities for the youth, a real grocery store for our residents, and a movie theater and  a water park.

properties.cultural_interests: Waterford values its water recreation highly. Over 11% of the township is comprised of lakes. Lake associations are the primary community hubs. Waterford shares a border with Keego Harbor and Sylvan Lake and our economies are related. We also share a border with Pontiac.
properties.economic_interests: Waterford is in the center of Oakland County. There are 34 lakes in the township, so water quality is a big issue. The majority of the population is employed in health care or the automotive industry.
properties.comm_activities:
Water, Police and Fire Services are provided by the township. Trash is not covered and paid for privately, though there is one company contracted to serve the whole township.
Major social centers are area parks and lakes, lake associations, and the two high schools, Waterford Mott and Waterford Kettering. 
Oakland Community College-Highland Lakes campus also provides some social opportunities.
properties.other_considerations: Demographics are shifting to include more people of color, although the population total numbers are very stable over the last 20 years. It is important that the concerns of people of color (about 17% of the total) are addressed by their district, while still adhering to the Voting Rights Act.
